## v8.1.0

### Additions

#### `trackFormControl`

Added `trackFormControl` function which creates a Form Control tracker instance. It tracks all properties of a `FormControl` instance and exposes them as signals and as RxJs observables. Tracked properties include:

- `value`
- `errors`
- `touched`
- `untouched`
- `pristine`
- `dirty`
- `status`
- `valid`
- `invalid`
- `pending`
- `disabled`
- `enabled`
- `validators`
- `asyncValidators`
- `touchedHasErrors` - computed property that returns `true` if the Form Control is touched and has any own errors
- `instance` - non-reactive property that holds the `FormControl` instance

##### `trackBoundControl`

`trackBoundControl` is a variant of `trackFormControl` that is meant to be used within a component that implements `ControlValueAccessor` to track the bound `FormControl` instance.

In most cases the tracker will be initialized before the component will be attached to the FormControl instance, so the tracker will do that automatically. In some cases, however, the tracker can be used inside a component or directive that does not implement `ControlValueAccessor`, in which case this functionality must be disabled throught the `options.attachValueAccessor` option.

#### `dualControlToRangeControlAdapter`

The `dualControlToRangeControlAdapter` is a function that allows to connect two `FormControl`s to a single component which outputs a `{ from: T, to: T }` kind of object. When used with the adapter, one form control will be bound to the `from` value, and the other to the `to` value.

The adapter synchronizes the touched, pristine, and disabled states between the two `FormControl`s, which is required for the adapter to work properly.

#### `ExtValidators`

Added `ExtValidators` static class containing additional validators.

**String validators**

- `ExtValidators.contains` checks if the value contains a specific substring
- `ExtValidators.notContains` checks if the value DOES NOT contain a specific substring
- `ExtValidators.lowercase` checks if the value is a lowercase string
- `ExtValidators.uppercase` checks if the value is a uppercase string
- `ExtValidators.namedPattern` works like the native `Validators.pattern`, but outputs the error into a customizable property name, instead of always being in the `pattern` property.
- `ExtValidators.ascii` checks if the value contains only ASCII characters
- `ExtValidators.base64` checks if the value contains only Base64 encoding characters
- `ExtValidators.hex` checks if the value contains only base-16 encoding characters
- `ExtValidators.octal` checks if the value contains only base-8 encoding characters
- `ExtValidators.binary` checks if the value contains only base-2 encoding characters

**Number validators**

- `ExtValidators.divisibleBy` checks if the value is a number divisble by the given divisor

**Computer-related validators**

- `ExtValidators.ipAddress` checks if the value is a valid IP address. Can be configured to accept only IPv4, only IPv6, or both
- `ExtValidators.uuid` checks if the value is a valid hex-encoded UUID
- `ExtValidators.hexColor` checks if the value is a valid hex color code. Both 3-character and 6-character codes are accepted.
- `ExtValidators.rgbColor` checks if the value is a valid rgb color string
- `ExtValidators.hslColor` checks if the value is a valid hsl color string
- `ExtValidators.password` checks if the value meets the configured password requirements. Outputs an object describing which rules were not met

**Array validators**

- `ExtValidators.arrayContains` checks if the value is an array that contains a specific value
- `ExtValidators.arrayNotContains` checks if the value is an array that DOES NOT contain a specific value
- `ExtValidators.arrayUnique` checks if the value is an array that contains only unique (non-repeating) values

**File validators**

All of the below file validators accept both a single File object and an array of File objects

- `ExtValidators.fileMaxSize` checks if the value is a File object which size in bytes meets the configured maximum value
- `ExtValidators.fileMinSize` checks if the value is a File object which size in bytes meets the configured minimum value
- `ExtValidators.fileExtension` checks if the value is a File object which extension matches any of the configured allowed extensions

### Bugfixes
- Infinite Scroll directive does not notify that the threshold is reached when the content does not fill the whole available vertical space (when there is no scrollbar)
  - It now immediately re-emits the threshold notification whenever it becomes active again

## v8.0.1

### Changes

- `HttpService` now allows for the `options.params` property to be null or undefined

## v8.0.0

### Breaking Changes

`ARD_FILEEXT_PIPE_DEFAULTS` and `ARD_FILESIZE_PIPE_DEFAULTS` injection tokens have been removed; a `ARD_FILE_PIPES_DEFAULTS` injection token replaces those two, combining properties of both. Use the `provideFilePipesDefaults` to provide default values for all file pipes at the same time.

### Additions

- Added `provideInfiniteScrollDefaults` that simlifies providing default values for the Infinite Scroll directive

## v7.8.0

### Additions

- Add support for array-based URLs in all HttpService methods.
  - The URL will be created by joining all parts together, like `path.join()` in Node JS.
- Created `formatFileExtension`, `formatFileName`, and `formatFileSize` functions.
  - Work exactly the same as their pipe equivalents, but can be easily used in typescript files.
  - They do not follow the default values provided using the provider functions!
- Added JSDoc comments to all file pipes.

## v7.7.1

### Changes

- Removed `isEmpty` property from `tupleSignal`, as it may never be empty.
- Simplified JSDoc comments on some new signals.

## v7.7.0

### Additions

- `arraySignal`:
  - Added `asReadonly` method.
  -
- Created `setSignal` - a signal for handling `Set` values.
- Created `mapSignal` - a signal for handling `Map` values.
- Created `tupleSignal` - a signal for handling tuples (fixed-length arrays).
- Created `stackSignal` - an array-based signal that behaves like the stack data structure.
- Created `queueSignal` - an array-based signal that behaves like the queue data structure.
- Created `counterSignal` - a number-based signal that allows easier incrementing, decrementing, and resetting of its value.

## v7.6.1

### Additions

- `arraySignal`:
  - Added `setAt` method for setting a value at a specific index.
  - Added `updateAt` method for updating a value at a specific index.

### Bugfixes

- Export `arraySignal` from public api, as it was inaccessible.

## v7.6.0

No changes.

## v7.5.0

### Additions

- Created `arraySignal` - a signal that simplifies handling array values.

### Bugfixes

- Fixed `debouncedSignal` and `throttledSignal` update methods not working.

## v7.4.0

### Changes

- `createHttpService` now uses method overloads instead of a single method with varying options.

## v7.3.0

### Additions

- Added a new value to `ViewportRelation`: InsideButTooLarge

### Changes

- `ArdViewportObserverRef`:
  - now supports the additional `ViewportRelation` value - used when the element is both partially above and partially below the viewport.

## v7.2.2

### Fixes

- Position was supposed to return the bottom position in reference to the bottom of the viewport. It is now fixed.
- Position was also supposed to include the margins, which are now included

## v7.2.0

### Additions

- Added two new values to `ViewportRelation`: PartiallyAbove and PartiallyBelow
- `ArdiumViewportObserverService`:
  - `observeElement` now supports passing in `ElementRef`s
  - Positions are now also updated on window resize, not only on element scroll
- `ArdViewportObserverRef`:
  - added `positon` signal: returns the current position of the element in reference to the top of the viewport

### Changes

- `ArdViewportObserverRef`:
  - now supports the additional `ViewportRelation` values.
  - `isInViewport` returns true if the element is _at least partially_ inside the viewport.

## v7.1.0

### Additions

- `ArdViewportObserverRef`: added `margins` property, which contains signals returning the currently set top & bottom margin values.

## v7.0.0

### Breaking Changes

- Major changes in `ArdViewportObserverRef`:
  - `viewportRelation` - changed type from `Observable<ViewportRelation>` to `Signal<ViewportRelation>`.
  - `isInViewport` - changed type from `Observable<boolean>` to `Signal<boolean | undefined>` - now when the viewport relation is `ViewportRelation.Undefined`, this returns `undefined`.
  - `enterViewport` and `leaveViewport` - removed.
- Major changes in `ArdiumViewportObserverService`:
  - `triggerRecheck()` - renamed to `recheckAll()`

### Additions

- `ArdiumViewportObserverService` now supports providing default config - added `ARD_VIEWPORT_OBSERVER_DEFAULTS` injection token and `provideViewportObserverDefaults` function for providing the default values (as well as the `ArdViewportObserverDefaults` type)
- Added `ViewportMargins` interface that represents the top & bottom margin values
- Added `ArdViewportObserverRef.recheck` that rechecks the viewport position of this specific element (before it was only possible by rechecking all registered observers)

### Internal Changes

- Refactored the entire `ArdViewportObserverRef` class
- Refactored much of the `ArdiumViewportObserverService`
- Every feature now has its exports handled by its own `index.ts` that tells what should be exported. The public api file now only exports from these `index.ts` files.

